hird, the macro forces shaping urban society include bureaucratic and governmental interventions not captured by a purely economic paradigm.Tajbakhsh examines these dimensions in the work of three major critical urban theorists of recent decades: Manuel Castells, David Harvey, and Ira Katznelson. He shows why the answers offered by Marxian urban theory to the questions of identity, space, and structure are unsatisfactory and why the perspectives of other intellectual traditions such as poststructuralism, feminism, Habermasian Critical Theory, and pragmatism can help us better understand the challenges facing contemporary cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMarxian school of sociology. 0aSociology, Urban. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aagency.  aanalysis.  abureaucratic.  acity life.  acity living.  acritical theory.  acritique.  adavid harvey.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  afeminism.  aidentity.  ainterdisciplinary.  aira katznelson.  aliterary analysis.  amanuel castells.  amarxist.  apoststructuralism.  ascholarly.  asocial studies.  aspace.  astructure.  aurban identity.  aurban life.  aurban living.  aurban theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022278640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092464240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924642/original  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-all